1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,186
demorec. Proof of work that's easy on the
eye.

2
00:00:04,308 --> 00:00:16,194
AI agents are writing more code than ever.
Reviewers need evidence that changes
actually work. Video is easy to consume,
but time-consuming to produce.

3
00:00:17,012 --> 00:00:30,100
Demorec produces short video demos from
scripts that execute real commands.
Because the script runs the actual
code—especially in CI without human
influence—the evidence is hard to fake.

4
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:40,663
In this demo, we'll walk through this
script in vim, start a web server, view
the page in the browser, and return to
terminal to see the request logs.

5
00:00:41,840 --> 00:00:44,662
Let's look at the script that's producing
this video.

6
00:00:51,691 --> 00:00:57,359
At the top, we set the output file,
dimensions, and voice for narration.

7
00:01:01,163 --> 00:01:04,037
Here we switch to presentation mode and
show slides.

8
00:01:07,838 --> 00:01:13,533
Then we switch to terminal mode. This is
where we open vim to show this very
script.

9
00:01:17,451 --> 00:01:21,238
Next, we switch to browser mode to
navigate to a web page.

10
00:01:25,151 --> 00:01:30,062
And back to terminal to see the server
logs. Mode switches are seamless.

11
00:01:31,444 --> 00:01:35,101
Now let's see it in action. We'll start a
server.

12
00:01:43,082 --> 00:01:44,597
And view it in the browser.

13
00:01:49,116 --> 00:01:53,139
The page loads. This is real—the server is
actually running.

14
00:01:53,004 --> 00:01:57,027
Back to the terminal—you can see the
request in the server logs.

15
00:02:01,031 --> 00:02:07,248
Every mode switch, every command, every
page load—it all actually executes.

16
00:02:08,604 --> 00:02:12,731
When recording finishes, you get an MP4
and subtitles.

17
00:02:18,224 --> 00:02:22,717
The reviewer watches 30 seconds instead of
reading 200 lines of code.

18
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:29,713
Demorec. Proof of work that's easy on the
eye. Check out the repo and try it on your
next PR.

